===Usage notes===
Pinoy is a slang that caught on with the Florante song “Akoy isang Pinoy” that became mainstream with Filipino culture(with the y appendaged after Fili''pino''Y) to denote their country of origin and background.

Kabayan is the proper way to address fellow Filipinos (To mean “coming from the the same part of town”)  

Noypi is a colloquial variation of pinoy(backwards). 

FLIP was thought of being derogatory although debatable. It was said to have been coined by American Soldiers from World War II to  mean “Fucking Little Island Person” although its true origin may be disputed, an urban legend.  

North American Filipinos have loosely used FLIP to describe their background. A plausible origin of the term comes from the word  ''Filipino'' shortened, sounds distinct and blends with popular culture.

